== Organization and administration == UNESP is governed by a [[Rector (academia)|rector]], appointed by the [[state governor]] who chooses the final candidate from a list of three nominees. The nominees are selected through elections, taking place among university’s academics held every four years. Usually, the governor selects the winner of those elections.{{Additional citation needed|date=August 2018}}
The rector presides over the University Council, composed of directors of every institute in the system and academic representatives. There are ten students representatives. The council makes most decisions that affect the university.{{Additional citation needed|date=August 2018}}
Each institute (there are campuses with more than one) has one director and a council who rules with a degree of autonomy.{{Additional citation needed|date=August 2018}}
=== UNESP rectors === * Luis Ferreira Martins (10/03/1976 – 09/03/1980) * Armando Octávio Ramos (10/03/1980 – 08/03/1984) * Manuel Nunes Dias (27/03/1984 – 31/07/1984), pro-tempore * Jorge Nagle (01/08/1984 – 16/01/1989) * Milton Barbosa Landim (17/01/1989 – 15/01/1993) * Artur Roquete de Macedo (16/01/1993 – 14/01/1997) * Antônio Manuel dos Santos Silva (15/01/1997 – 14/01/2001) * José Carlos Souza Trindade (15/01/2001 – 14/01/2005) * Marcos Macari (15/01/2005 - 14/01/2009) * Herman Jacobus Cornelis Voorwald (15/01/2009 - 14/01/2013) * Julio Cezar Durigan (since 15/01/2013-2017) *[[Sandro Roberto Valentini]] (2017-2021)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.unesp.br/portal#!/reitor|title=Unesp - Universidade Estadual Paulista - Portal|website=www2.unesp.br|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>
== Academics == UNESP employs about 3,500 teachers, in addition to another 10,600 employees in various positions. The university provides 171 options for undergraduate courses in 62 higher education professions, with a total of over 45,000 students, of which 5,600 new professionals are trained annually by UNESP. About 10,000 students study in 118 postgraduate programs, with 117 academic masters, 6 professional masters and 93 academic doctorates.
The academic year at UNESP follows a two-semester schedule, with slight differences depending on the courses and programs chosen. The spring semester runs from August - December and the fall semester from February - June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.unesp.br/portal#!/international/campus-life/plan-a-visit|title=Unesp - Universidade Estadual Paulista - Portal|website=www2.unesp.br|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>
In the recent decade Brazil has generally become more widely recognized as a good academic environment (developing alongside the rest of the countries economy).<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2012-09-12|title=Spotlight on Latin America|url=https://www.nature.com/naturejobs/science/articles/10.1038/nj0389|journal=Nature Jobs|doi=10.1038/nj0389|issn=1476-4687}}</ref> But with the economic crisis some universities in Brazil have struggled in the last years; the number of publications authored and co-authored from UNESP however, has continually risen since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.natureindex.com/news-blog/brazils-subsumed-science-sector-struggles-to-stay-afloat|title=Brazil’s subsumed science sector struggles to stay afloat|website=www.natureindex.com|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>
=== Admissions === Admissions to UNESP are restricted by a state-wide, general admissions exam, known as ''[[vestibular]]''. For [[architecture]], [[arts]] and [[design]] undergraduate courses, additional specific exams are required.
Prepared by VUNESP, an institution specialized in exams organization, UNESP vestibular are held on three days, separated in two phases.
# The first phase consists of 90 questions in the following disciplines: [[philosophy]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[mathematics]], [[chemistry]], [[biology]], [[geography]], [[history]], [[physics]] and [[English language|English]] or [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. # The second phase of exams, separated in two days, is made up of specific questions in Humane and Natural Sciences on the first day. The second day of the second phase consists of specific questions in Languages (Portuguese and English or Spanish) and a writing exam.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/12/29/world/rio-journal-for-brazil-s-college-bound-a-brutal-test-of-mettle.html|title=Rio Journal; For Brazil's College-Bound, a Brutal Test of Mettle|last=Rohter|first=Larry|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>
A student can only apply for a single course in the São Paulo State University system, preventing a simultaneous application for e.g. History and Geography.
=== Exchange programmes === UNESP has 140 international exchange and cooperation agreements with institutions of higher education in 52 countries. The main exchange countries for UNESP are currently [[Argentina]], [[Canada]], [[China]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Portugal]], [[Spain]], [[Russia]], the [[United States]] and [[Scotland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.unesp.br/portal#!/international/study|title=Unesp - Universidade Estadual Paulista - Portal|website=www2.unesp.br|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unan.unesp.br/guidaprofissoes/pdf/m14_u6_21092017-13-40-56.pdf|title=Career guide UNESP - International Exchange|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
To further support international students the university launched a program called "International Courses" in 2013. The program comprised four different areas initially: [[Agricultural science|Agricultural Sciences]], [[Alternative energy|Alternative Energy]], [[Dentistry]] and [[Literature]] and [[Linguistics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.unesp.br/portal#!/international-courses|title=Unesp - Universidade Estadual Paulista - Portal|website=www2.unesp.br|access-date=2018-08-15}}</ref>
